\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Proof-mode feasibility matrix. Of the modes \emph  {produced} on the target hardware by the zkVMs, none is dependably zero-knowledge: the SP1 rows are not zero-knowledge, the RISC~Zero receipt carries no formally established zero-knowledge guarantee, and the only zero-knowledge mode the zkVM toolchain exposes (row~3, a pairing wrap) is neither post-quantum nor produced within the memory bound, which is the dual obstruction. The zero-knowledge mode that is produced on this hardware is the static-circuit Aurora run (last row; \S  \ref {ssec:aurora-ref}). \textsuperscript  {$\dagger $}The zero-knowledge-enabled Aurora run is now measured (last row); the zk-disabled row is retained for comparison. Both Aurora rows achieve $107.5$ bits, below the $\lambda =128$ target. \textsuperscript  {$\ddagger $}RISC~Zero's succinct receipt carries zero-knowledge blinding, but the vendor disclaims a formal zero-knowledge guarantee, so we treat the receipt as not dependably zero-knowledge~\cite  {risc0zkadvisory,l2beatzk} (Section~\ref {sec:security}). The SHA-3 row is a control, not a deployable PLUM variant.}}{99}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:proof-mode}{{7}{99}{}{table.7}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Circuit/parameter regeneration footprint ($N_{\mathsf  {circ}},N_{\mathsf  {param}}$ of Definition~\ref {def:update-churn}). The static-circuit regime regenerates and re-audits its R1CS and constraint-dependent parameters on every localised change; the zkVM absorbs a change as a guest-program edit, leaving the universal relation unchanged ($N_{\mathsf  {circ}}=N_{\mathsf  {param}}=0$), except where the change crosses the precompile boundary. \textsuperscript  {$\ast $}The Loquat~$\to $~PLUM swap moves the hash field from $\mathbb  {F}_{p^2}$ (127-bit) to the 199-bit $\mathbb  {F}_p$, so the field-specific Griffin AIR is regenerated (\S  \ref {ssec:update-churn} carve-out). The components $N_{\mathsf  {src}},N_{\mathsf  {audit}}$ are reported in prose below.}}{100}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:churn}{{8}{100}{}{table.8}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Per-change recompile components for a non-preprocessing (Aurora) versus a preprocessing (Fractal) transparent argument on the same $127$-bit-field harness, M5~Pro 24~GB. The $2^{10}$--$2^{14}$ rows are synthetic R1CS instances; the $2^{19}$ row is the single-Loquat-verification relation at the BDEC building-block size. Aurora has no per-circuit indexer (parameter setup flat at ${\sim }\mu $s, so $R_{\mathsf  {static}}$ stays sub-second); Fractal's indexer is superlinear and exceeds $24$~GB at the $2^{19}$ size (OOM mid-indexer). The zkVM regenerates no circuit.}}{100}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:rstatic-fractal}{{9}{100}{}{table.9}{}}
